Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysicists at the University of California, Santa Cruz, have studied turbulent mixing and its effect on chemical homogeneity in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of specialists will allow to search among the stars relatives, that is, those that originated from the same cluster.
The results of their research were published in the journal Nature, and briefly they can be found on the website of the university.
The reason for the same chemical composition of the nearest stars is the turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas that preceded the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the star cluster, by its chemical composition it is possible to determine its place of birth and region of formation of relatives stars.
Previously, scientists had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster could lead to differences in its chemical content from that of its relatives in the cluster.
The results of the modeling conducted by astrophysicists show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, scientists using a supercomputer modeled two streams of interstellar gas, which together formed a cloud.
For several million years, this object is transformed by its own gravity into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists added label paints to the initial gas flows and found that thanks to the rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud, a high degree of chemical uniformity is achieved.
According to astrophysicists, their study proves that it is possible to search for stars related to the chemical composition, as well as to determine possible regions of formation of such objects.
