Recalling the very American ideal that labour rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Allison and John Lewis proposed a bill that would protect trade unions as civil law.
“Where trade unions are, there are middle-class jobs,” says Allison, a Minnesota Democrat who is a co-chair of the Progressive Party Congress.
That's why I'm proud to present the Workers' Rights Enlargement Act along with the symbol of the civil rights movement John Lewis.
This innovative bill will give workers the same legal opportunities in discrimination against the organization of trade unions as in other forms of discrimination, stopping the forces of the opponents of trade unions.
Amendment of the Labour Relations Regulation Act in such a way as to enable workers who face discrimination for their participation in the organization of trade unions to seek justice in civil courts - and to receive compensation for damages and fines - a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is no doubt not a radical initiative – at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Allison, Lewis and the co-authors of the bill are offering is to remember a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that trade unions have faced in recent years — in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country — Americans have once supported countries around the world in adopting, expanding, and respecting labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution drawn up to ensure that Hideki Tojo’s militarized autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions play a role in forming a new Japan, they included a text that explicitly acknowledged that “the right of workers to organize, to negotiate, and to collective action is guaranteed.”
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans write a constitution that ensured that Adolf Hitler’s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers will need to be organized and heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: “The right to form associations with the aim of protecting and improving working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every person and every profession or sphere of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will have no legal force; measures aimed at these purposes will be deemed unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was the chairman of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the World Declaration on Human Rights, which in 1948 would be adopted by the United Nations to protect its interests in the United Nations as a global agreement, Roosevelt and its constituents included a guarantor.
For generations, Americans have accepted as a proper basic rule that labour rights are human rights.
When that country consulted other countries on how to create civil and democratic societies, the Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions – and to participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and governmental institutions – must be enshrined.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to an organization and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement has not undermined the strength of the nation, but has increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions, trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised the whole nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how we should.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the expansion of civil rights protection to prevent discrimination against trade unions - has long been ripe.
Keith Allison and John Lewis revive the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
Judge Temporarily Blocks Law That Could Close All Abortion Clinics in Louisiana
In the United States, a federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the enactment of the Louisiana law, which his supporters say is likely to shut down all five abortion clinics in the state.
