However, the judge’s decision means that at the moment doctors can continue to make legal abortions, continuing to seek such powers.
"The justices will be allowed to work legally, continuing to take action to obtain the powers," Justice John DeGrewells said in a statement.
The hearing will be appointed during the month in which the judge will make a more permanent decision under this law.
Proponents of the right to abortion were pleased to meet this decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital credentials.
“Today’s decision ensures that Louisiana women will be protected from a fraudulent law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights,” said Nancy Nortap, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which filed a lawsuit against the law’s cessation of action from three out of five people.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision relates to the doctors from the two clinics, who were not the plaintiffs in the case, and also applied for admissions.
Louisiana is among the 11 states that have passed such laws, and courts have recently recognized such measures as unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law, which would shut down most of the remaining clinics in the state, were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Fighters for the right to abortion, along with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, say that the laws on admission powers impose restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortions object that such measures are aimed at protecting women’s health, although some have also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who makes abortions in Louisiana has the authority to be admitted to the hospital, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all the other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing this procedure, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing this procedure, the group said.
Criticizing the decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish doctors who make abortions while their claims to the decision are pending.
