Angelina Jolie and her brother James released a video of the memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women living in rural Australia are at a higher risk of dying from ovarian cancer than those living in cities.
Researchers analyzed disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 percent lived five years after being diagnosed.
Lead researcher Susan Jordan from the QIMR Berghofer Institute of Medical Research reported that the chances of dying during the study were 20 percent higher in those living in regions and remote areas of the state than in those living in urban areas.
NEW MEDICINAL PROTECTION: New Drugs May Slow Lung Cancer and Ovarian Cancer
Researchers tracked the women’s medical path over seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that the age of the woman at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socioeconomic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Women who were older and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those who lived in regions or remote areas of the state, the probability of dying during the study was 20 percent higher than for those who lived in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside cities are more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that an untimely diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment are possible facts.
“This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynecological oncology, and they are mainly located in large cities,” she said.
Despite improving the quality of telemedicine services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that an increase in the number of outbound services that will allow specialists to treat women closer to home, and support programs for people who are undergoing treatment far from their home, may
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographic location, the study found that longevity among women with ovarian cancer was rare, emphasizing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
