The essence of online-to-offline (O2O) commerce is to attract online shoppers so that they come to ordinary offline stores or buy other traditional services.
A classic example of O2O are coupon sales services like Groupon or Vigoda.ru.
“O2O is the biggest ‘pier’ in online commerce,” said CEO Wanda Wang Jianglin.
“Now there is no real O2O site in China, and in this situation, the odds are roughly equal,” he said.
China’s e-commerce market is the largest in the world, and, according to McKinsey & Co., its volume will increase more than three times by 2015 compared to 2011, to $395 billion.
The number of Chinese Internet users has grown to 632 million, according to official statistics from Bloomberg: this is more than the population of any country in the world, with the exception of India.
