A genetic disorder is often incorrectly diagnosed.
The British woman said she spent many years thinking she would die after being misdiagnosed.
Karen Rogers spent most of her teenage years thinking that she only had a few years to live after she was diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Sharko-Mari-Tuta disease (SMT) - a group of hereditary disorders that lead to damage to nerves outside the brain and spinal cord.
The charity CMT UK reported that incorrectly diagnosed is a common problem among people with MS because so little is known about this condition.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK are thought to have SMT, which can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, insecure walking, and squeezed toes.
Patients may feel numbness or pain, and the condition does not heal and progresses, which means that the symptoms worsen over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Frederick’s (AF) attack – a condition for which the prognosis was very bad.
Rogers thought she would be tied to a wheelchair by the time she was 18, and die before she turned 30.
The mother of two children, now 51, said: “As a child, I knew I couldn’t do what others did.
I fell every day, and it took me more time.
I could never ride roller skates or skateboard with other kids, and I had a lot of bullying in school because of the way I walked and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release the Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she looked into the medical card when her doctor left the room and it was written that she had AF.
“I felt guilty because I pushed my nose where it shouldn’t be, and so I didn’t tell anyone, but I came home, found information about the condition in the library and wrote to the AF Association,” she said.
When I received the information in response, I was shocked and experienced the most terrible panic as possible.
I thought that I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die before I turned 25, and that I would gradually lose all my abilities in the meantime.
I went through this alone, and I planned my own funeral.
She said that by the time she was 17, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she thought, and asked her doctor about it.
He just stood up, hugged me and said, “My dear, I don’t think you have this disease because you’d already be in a wheelchair.”
I think you have something that poses much less of a threat to life.
After several genetic tests, she was found to have SMT.
“When he explained what an SMT was, I thought I was pulling a happy ticket,” she said.
The UK charity SMT has announced a month of information on SMT to try to draw attention to the disease.
The tax burden on entrepreneurs in the Washington area is growing as the economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales, and new jobs.
It also means higher taxes.
Accounts for state and local-level tax payments for companies across the country have risen moderately last year, as the recovery of the economy accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and companies in the Washington Zone are no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia combined paid $27.6 billion into the state treasury and locally in fiscal 2013, up 3.8 percent from the $26.6 billion raised in 2012.
The tax burden on business by state and local level increased by 4.3 percent last year to $671 billion, up from 3.9 percent a year earlier, and it was the third consecutive year of growth after year-on-year when accounts fell in 2009.
Taxes levied by the state rose faster, 4.3 percent more than local taxes, 3.9 percent, according to a study conducted by a company providing professional services, Ernst & Young and the State Taxation Center, a policy group.
More than half of the county’s tax revenues, 56 percent, are taxed on entrepreneurs, while 36% of Maryland’s tax revenues are taxed on firms.
Virginia, with 28 percent, brings the lowest amount of tax revenue, proportionately, from entrepreneurs.
The rise in tax revenues is largely driven by a return to the company’s previous value level, the researchers say, which raised property taxes by 3.7 percent this year after three years in a row, when the growth was less than 1 percent.
While a large portion of these revenues come from large states, such as California, New York and Texas, it seems that the same is happening in the Washington area.
Companies in the county, Maryland, and Virginia collectively paid $10 billion in state and local real estate taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012 – an increase of 4.2 percent compared to the previous year.
However, the observed return of real estate value does not have any similar effect on the growth of tax revenues by the state and at the local level in Maryland, where property taxes barely exceed one-fifth of companies’ tax accounts.
The companies of Virginia and the District of Columbia pay about half of the tax bills per state and locally in the form of property taxes.
“What’s happening in Maryland is that such a large part of their real estate, especially the tax base around the District of Columbia, belongs to either the government or a non-profit organization that doesn’t pay taxes on real estate,” said Douglas Lindholm, executive director.
Thus, Maryland is forced to rely much more, for example, on income taxes to pay for the same services that exist in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully explained by the recovery of the real estate market.
Entrepreneurs’ incomes also appear to be being adjusted, according to this data.
Companies in the region have declared a state-level corporate income tax of $2.3 billion, an increase of $2.1 billion compared to 2012.
Maryland has raised $1 billion in corporate income tax revenue, the largest in the region.
Although the trends are in the same direction, the tax burden on entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three locations.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was at the same level as the country-average, 4.3 percent, while growth in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 percent.
In Virginia alone, tax revenues rose below the average, equal to 4.1 per cent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax in the three jurisdictions (each of which had the same corporate rate) equal to 6%.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25%, while in the county it is relatively high – 9.975%.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year showed that Virginia has lower taxes for entrepreneurs by state and local level and, in general, a more favorable climate in terms of taxes for entrepreneurs than in Maryland.
The district was not evaluated in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from its neighbours from the south.
North Carolina has recently signed a law that lowers the corporate rate this year from 6.9 percent to 6 percent, just like in Virginia, and the rate will fall to 5 percent next year.
If the state continues to meet its tax revenue targets next year, the law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs up to 3% by 2017.
Meanwhile, the small business in the Washington area seems to feel better and thus pays more taxes on the state and local level, according to a recent study.
Taxes for entrepreneurs paid in the form of individual income tax by small business owners - the transitional structure that most small firms are based on - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia have increased by 20 percent in the previous year.
Researchers say the trend and increase in business tax revenues across the country are likely to continue this year, with revenues from turnover taxes in state and local governments rising by 6.2 percent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period.
However, the Washington area may be lagging behind, as the fall in federal spending affects the labor market in the region.
