MPs proposed to speed up the entry into force of the Personal Data Act
In case of success of the initiative, the data of Russians will not be stored on servers abroad from January 1, 2015
The State Duma introduced a draft law that provides for the transfer of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law on personal data of Russians - from September 1, 2016 to January 1, 2015.
The initiative is placed at the base of the legislative activity of the lower house.
Its authors were the deputies of the State Duma Vadim Déngin, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Yevgeny Fedorov ("United Russia"), Vladimir Parakhin ("Just Russia") and Alexander Yushchenko (CPRF).
Such a change, in the opinion of the authors of the initiative, will contribute to a more rapid and effective safeguarding of the rights of Russian citizens to the preservation of personal data and the observance of the secrecy of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks.
The law, the entry into force of which parliamentarians hasten, obliges to store on the territory of the Russian Federation personal data of Russians processed via the Internet.
It also makes mandatory the recording, systematization, accumulation, storage, refinement and extraction of personal data of Russian citizens, in databases located on the territory of Russia, as well as the indication of the location of such databases.
In addition, the law grants Roskomnadzor the right on the basis of a court decision to restrict access to information processed in violation of the legislation of the Russian Federation in the field of personal data.
The law also proposes the creation of so-called "black lists" of infringing websites - an automated information system "Register of Infringers of the rights of personal data subjects".
This law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The authors of the draft law were Andrey Lugova and Vadim Dengin from LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko from KPRF.
Déngin and Yushchenko are also among the authors of the current draft law on the transfer of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who do not have data centers in the Russian Federation will have to pay for the rent
Commenting on the draft law introduced today in the State Duma, the first deputy head of the Duma Committee on Information Policy Leonid Levin said that he sees no problems for the transfer of the date of entry into force of the law on the protection of personal data.
According to him, those companies that by January 1, 2015 will not have their own repositories of personal data of Russians in the territory of the Russian Federation, will be able to rent them, for example, "in "Rostelekom", which has already been told by the owner of the company many times that they are ready to provide their servers to the Group, the company has already leased, and the company has already leased.
“In addition, there are several independent data centers ready to cooperate in this area,” he added.
"If companies decide to enforce the law and continue to work in the territory of the Russian Federation, I see no problems - they will get technological opportunities for placement," Levin said.
Controversial Bill
Immediately after the publication of the bill, the Russian Association of Electronic Communications expressed concern that in the event of the adoption of the bill, the Russians will no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
In particular, we are talking about the services of online booking of airline tickets and hotels.
According to the association, "the draft law deprives subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation of the right to dispose of their own data by imperatively determining that their recording, systematization, etc. should be provided only in databases located on the territory of the Russian Federation".
The RAEC statement stresses that a more effective measure would be to create a mechanism to inform the user about where the recording is taking place and to systematize his personal data.
In this case, it will be possible to choose the territory in which these actions will be carried out.
The adoption of such bills on the "localization" of personal data in other countries has led to the abandonment of global services and significant economic losses.
