The savings certificate will be made anonymous and irrevocable
The Ministry of Finance wants to ban savings certificates on the presenter, but will allow banks to make them an analogue of an irrevocable contribution.
The Ministry of Finance is preparing a bill that will ban savings certificates on the applicant.
Recently, this tool is gaining popularity, as the rates here are higher than for bank deposits.
The fact is that savings certificates on the applicant do not fall into the deposit insurance system, and they are cheaper for the bank, as there is no need to make deductions to the Fund of the Deposit Insurance Agency (ASV).
The spiciness of the situation is that this step is planned to be taken due to small and medium-sized banks distributing such certificates, and it will affect Sberbank and Bank of Moscow, which, according to the ASV, control 98% of the profile market.
And the Bank of Moscow’s share, according to the agency, is about 3.5%.
The problem, explained in ASV, is that the clients of a small bank, who bought such a certificate, in case of revocation of his licenses try to get money in ASV.
Some investors, who do not have sufficient financial literacy and buy savings certificates on the presenter, may assume that their investments are insured.
A justified lack of insurance payments on these certificates in the event of the withdrawal of the license from the bank can lead to misunderstanding and social tension.
In the practice of the agency, there were cases when the holders of presentation certificates tried to recover insurance reimbursement through the court," - said in the ASV.
The problem, of course, is deliberate.
After all, nobody will pay buyers of certificates anyway, because they have no right to reimbursement from the state under the law.
If the instrument was not insured in the ASW, it would also prohibit metal accounts on which citizens ' funds are accounted for in grams of one of the four metals - gold, silver, platinum and palladium.
After all, these accounts also do not fall into the deposit insurance system, but on their existence so far no one is trying.
The most likely thing is that the certificates on the presenter are a very convenient security that can actually play the role of quasi-denominated.
At the same time, their movement is virtually uncontrollable: any customer of the bank can buy a certificate, pass it on to any citizen, and before such a certificate can be issued, many owners can change it.
It is no coincidence that the draft law stipulates that a savings certificate must necessarily be a nominal securities, which must be stored in the depositary.
And in order to sweeten the pill to banks, such certificates are allowed to be issued without the right of early repayment.
That is, the analogy of the irrevocable deposit is introduced, which bankers have long dreamed of.
