A potential way to steal photos of nude celebrities has been discovered
Mass hacking of star accounts may have been caused by a vulnerability in the Find My Phone app.
A potential scenario for the development of events was described by the resource The Next Web.
A Python script was published on Github, which allowed you to select passwords for Apple’s Find My Phone service.
This service allows you to track the location of the iPhone.
To access it, the same link of login and Apple ID is used as for access to the Apple iCloud cloud, from which photos of celebrities were stolen.
The script enabled the password from Find My Phone to be recognized by the override method.
With this method, all sorts of combinations of characters are entered consistently, starting with the most commonly used passwords.
The author of the script claimed that in the Find My Phone service the number of passwords to enter is unlimited.
With the correct organization of the security system after several unsuccessful attempts to enter the wrong password, the account should be blocked and inform the user of the attempted hack.
Due to the vulnerability, users did not receive any messages about trying to pick up a password for their account.
The hackers recognized the password from Apple ID and used it to access iCloud.
According to a hackapp user’s Twitter message, the vulnerability was discovered two days ago on Saturday, and it was written with a scripting program for selecting passwords.
At the moment, the vulnerability is closed: after five attempts, access to the service is blocked.
The resource contacted Hackapp user and he noted that the aforementioned vulnerability is characteristic of many services, but noted that there is no evidence that such a vulnerability was used to access the "star" account.
