SKR discontinues investigation into the Tu-204 disaster in Vnukovo
The Investigative Committee of Russia (SCR) has terminated the criminal case for the fact of the crash of the Tu-204 aircraft of the airline Red Wings.
This is reported by the press service of the department.
The decision was made in connection with the death of the commander of the aircraft and the flight engineer.
The forensic examination showed that the cause of the disaster was the increased rate of action on boarding, the failure of the crew of standard procedures on boarding, as well as the unintentional exit of the engines to the increased speed of direct traction.
The Tu-204 aircraft of the Red Wings, followed by the flight Prague-Moscow, crashed on December 29, 2012 during a landing at the Moscow airport of Vnukovo.
The aircraft rolled over the runway and set on fire.
At the scene of the incident, the commander of the aircraft, a second pilot and a flight engineer were killed.
Two pilots were taken to medical facilities, where they later died from the injuries they received.
Three other pilots, who were hospitalized with severe bodily injuries, underwent long-term treatment.
In addition, the driver of the car, which was driven at the time of the accident on the Kyiv highway, suffered serious bodily injury.
There were no passengers on board the aircraft.
After the accident, the D.A. carried out a check at the Red Wings, during which numerous violations were detected.
In February 2013, the airline’s license was suspended.
The company resumed operations in the summer of 2013.
