Anger proved to be the most universal and functional emotion of man
The expression of a face is biologically universal to humanity, and each organ and group of muscles involved in its creation is not accidental, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, scientists in Australia and the United States have found.
They told about their discoveries in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly read about them in a press release from the University of California at Santa Barbara.
The angry expression of the face - tilted and lowered down the eyebrows, stretched in a thin line of the lips, swollen nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and makes it even blind from birth to children who have never seen it, notes lead author of the study Aaron.
As part of a major research project dedicated to the nature of anger, scientists have found that this emotion has arisen for the effective conduct of disputes during a conflict.
The more physical harm one person can do to another, the more he has the ability to dictate his conditions, and he reports it to the interlocutor through anger.
Researchers have found evidence and another hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to be angry and go to court, consider themselves entitled to impose on others unfavourable conditions, and also prefer force-based conflict resolution methods to peaceful ones.
Refusing from the fact that anger is primarily an “emotion of bargaining,” the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create the angry expression of the face should represent the angry individual more powerful and dangerous than the contemporaneous person to agree with the conditions in the eyes of the interlocutor – and thus make it possible to do so.
To verify this hypothesis, the researchers modeled on the computer a person, where each of the seven elements of the angry person were present or absent, and showed them to informants.
Although the lowered eyebrows or the protruding chin separately did not make the face bad, the person depicted with such traits was recognized by the participants of the study unanimously.
Man’s anger, as with animals, expresses a threat: an exaggerated manifestation of one’s own strength, forcing one to accept and obey.
A person inflates the nostrils and presses the lips for the same purpose as a frog that inflates, or a baboon that demonstrates its claws.
Anger is triggered by the refusal of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form, as effectively as possible demonstrating the opposite side of the consequences of this refusal.
But the most striking thing is that none of the components of the angry face is arbitrary, they all express the same thing,” said anthropologist John Tubi.
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles to the broadcasting company "Crimea"
The Ministry of Communications proposed to allocate 250 million rubles from the federal budget of the autonomous non-profit organization "Crimea Radio Company" in 2014.
This is stated in the draft decision of the government prepared by the department, with which "Lenta.ru" became acquainted.
According to the explanatory note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed "to cover the costs of creating the conditions for large-scale informational illumination of the socio-economic situation and development of the modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea".
In particular, the allocated money is supposed to refurbish the hardware studio unit, video wall, central hardware and video server.
It is also planned to acquire a mobile TV station and a satellite transmitter.
In addition, the company will pay for the use of fiber-optic communication line (VOLS) and energy system repairs.
Subsidies will be provided within the federal budget funds provided for the Ministry of Communications.
The State TV Broadcasting Company "Crimea" was established in 1959, broadcasting in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, the coverage of the television signal of the broadcasting company is more than 75 percent of the territory of the peninsula.
In 2011, "Teleradiocompany "Crimea" received a license for television broadcasting in digital format.
